## Greek culture is very influential
- Particularly colorful depiction of the afterlife
- Similar monsters, personalities, landmarks
- Known for their exploration of [[Unsorted/Philosophy\|Philosophy]]


- Most information about their religion comes from poets, playwrights, and philosophers
	- Little academic analysis of it
	- It's much looser than monotheistic religions
	- There's a great deal of variety in portrayals!

- Religion is known as the "12 Gods Religion"


## Sources
### Hesiod
- Lived around 750-650BCE
- Acording to legend, he was a sheep farmer who was visited by one of the muses
	- Muses are great sources of artistic inspiration
	- IE Dwarf fortress moods
	- The muses are an explanation for inspiration, and flow states
- Works
	- ***Theogeny*** (Birth of the Gods)
		- Detailed description of the origin of the universe
		- Includes extensive family tree of the gods
		- Describes brutal power struggles between 3 generations of gods
			- Uranos, Kronos, Zeus
				- Familial line, primary gods of each generation
			- Brutal
				- Castration, cannibalism, full scale war
					- The gen 3 gods aren't as into that as the early ones
					- Zeus was last of his brothers to be eaten 
				- Final war lasted for a whole decade
		- Eventually won by the ***Olympians***, led by ***Zeus***
		- The losers are immortal gods
			- Can't be killed
			- So they're sent to ***Tartarus***, an inescapable prison

### Homer
- Modern scholars believe that Homer isn't just one person
	- Rather the Homeric tradition, retold for centuries before being written down
- Source of most knowledge of ancient Greek [[Class - Roots of Hell/Burial\|Burial]] 
	- A body left unburied to be eaten by scavengers is the worst fate
	- The Prothesis
		- Laying out of the body
		- Steps
			- Washing
			- Anounting with oil
			- Dressed with new clothes
				- Closest they get to Grave goods
			- Put on high bed in house
			- Friends, relatives, come to mourn
	- Ekphora
		- Funeral procession
		- Happens just before dawn
		- Body is taken out on cart, surrounded by friends and family
	- The Internment (Burial) or cremation of the remains
		- Cremation used to be the ancient standard
			- Bones and ash collected in an urn
		- Later on, burial became more common
- Wrote The iliad
	- Depicts middling part of the Trojan war
	- Not the beginning or the end
- Wrote ***The Oddysey / Odysseus***

#### Persephone
- [[Unsorted/Hell Tropes#Dying vegetation god myths\|Hell Tropes#Dying vegetation god myths]]

###### Her story
-  Daughter of Demeter (Harvest goddess)
	- Often both depicted together in ceremonies and rituals
- While she's picking flowers, a chasm opens up and [[Class - Roots of Hell/Ruler of Hell\|Hades]] comes out of it
	- They are pretty much opposite gods
	- He [[Unsorted/Sins#Lust\|lusts]] after her, she's fertile
		- So he kidnaps her, and takes her back to [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hades]]
- Abduction is known as the Rape of Persephone
	- Not modern definition of rape, mostly refers to kidnapping
	- Many artists are drawn to this
		- Rape of Proserpina
			- ![Pasted image 20220919150104.png|200](data:image/png;base64,)
			- ![Pasted image 20220919150115.png](data:image/png;base64,)
- Local shepherd, Eubuleus, sees it happen while tending to his pigs
	- ALL HIS PIGS SINK INTO HADES
- Demeter is horrified, searched the world
	- Neglects her duties as harvest goddess,
		- Nothing grew on the surface of the Earth
	- Also depicted as a threat
- Starving people get Zeus to help them
	- So Zeus forces Hades to return Persephone to Demeter
- Before she returns she is tricked into eating some pomegranete seeds [[Unsorted/Hell Tropes#Don't eat food in the underworld\|Hell Tropes#Don't eat food in the underworld]]
	- Each seed traps her there for a month
	- [[Unsorted/Hell Tropes#Dying vegetation god myths\|Hell Tropes#Dying vegetation god myths]]
	- Explains seasonal change
		- Winter: While Persephone is in Hades, Demeter makes the world a barren place
		- Spring: When she is returned, the world bursts with new life
- Common Greek ritual: Thesmophoria
	- 3-day festival to honor Persephone and Demeter
	- Women only, no men allowed
	- Rites performed are kept secret from men
		- To cheer up Demeter
	- Activities
		- Day 1: Andos (Ascent)
			- The women gather and set up the tents they'll be staying in
		- Day 2: Nesteia
			- The women all fast, reflect on Demeter mourning Persephone
		- Day 3: Kalligeneia (Beautiful birth)
			- Women pray for their own fertility
		- Ritual obsenity: Women make obscene jokes about men
		- Pigs are sacrificed and the remains are thrown into a pit to be left for 3-12 months
			- Honors Eubuleus
			- Women later retrieve the remains to purify them and place them on altars
- All leads to Persephone having a dual identity, each for half a year:
	- The young maiden, damsel in distress
		- Her Kore/Maiden persona
	- The queen of the underworld
		- Likely due to [[Syncretism\|Syncretism]] with an older female god
		- Much more frightening/intimidating
		- She is the one who acts upon curses that people cast upon eachother
		- Forbidden to speak her name
- Other Greek ritual: Eleusinian Mysteries ^Eleusenian-Mysteries
	- Also about fertility, but more about death and the afterlife
	- Many separate rituals, cults, and sects
		- People are sworn to secrecy, so there is little record of the specifics
	- 3 Phases
		1. Descent; loss
		2. Searching
		3. Ascent
		4. After fasting, participants drink the Kykeon, [[Unsorted/Drugs\|a powerful psychadelic]]
	- A way to become friends with Persephone
		- So that she'll take care of you in the afterlife
	- Cicero's description
		- Thinks it's contributed greatly to human life
		- To live more happily and die with a better hope



## Orpheus
- Legendary musician and poet, who could charm anything or anyone, even inanimate objects
	- Has some divine heritage
		- Sometimes considered the son of Persephone
			- So he'd basically be asking his mom for a favor
- Had a very bad wedding
	- Wife: Eurydice
	- A satyr shows up, and kills his wife by throwing her into a viper pit
		- Representation of wild unfulfilled urges
- Orpheus played the saddest song ever, brought everybody around to tears
- Somebody suggests that he travel to [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hades (Place)]] and usehis music to convince them to return his wife
	- [[Unsorted/Descent Motif\|Descent Motif]]
- [[Class - Roots of Hell/Ruler of Hell\|Hades (God)]] is greatly moved by his music, so they accept, with a condition
	- He cannot look back at her until she is on the surface
	- "No problem"
	- Long, difficult journey
		- But he's very careful not to look
- When he crossed the threshold, he turned in excitement to look at her
	- He was out, but she was still in the underworld!
	- Her shade vanishes, and she's gone forever
- He DID make it out, which caused The Orphic Cult to form around him
	- Closely associated with Dionysus / Dionysian cult
	- Extremely influential for early Greco-Roman religions like [[Unsorted/Early Christianity\|Early Christianity]]

- Focuses on Dionysus and his servant Xanthias

- They want to go to Hades because all the good playwrights are dead

## Tartarus (hell for gods)
- Distant abyss, FAR below the Earth
- Same distance from Earth as Earth is from the heavens
	- Anvil falling for 9 straight days
- Surrounded by a fence of bronze
- Sky holds the roots of the Earth
- In the center is ***The Abyss***
	- Bottomless pit
		- Fall for a year without landing
- Titans, cyclops, and monsters also go there
- Later also was described as a place for the worst of all mortals to go to suffer


## Hades (hell for mortals)
- Originally a neutral realm for the dead with no sorting
	- Later developed as society matured
- Everyone goes to Hades, little sorting [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife#Sorting\|Punishing afterlife#Sorting]]
- Some Greeks tried to reconcile the existence of both Tartarus and Hades
	- Later described as a bottomless pit within Hades
- [[Class - Roots of Hell/Ruler of Hell\|Hades]] (the god) is the ruler of the underworld
	- Rarely depicted, taboo to even use his real name
	- When depicted, usually with Cerberus
	- Feared and hated, but *not especially evil*
		- But can be *very viscious* to intruders or those who cheat him
	- Married to Persephone

## Influential figures:

### Plato
- (428-348 BCE)
- So influential that previous pilosophers are referred to as pre-platonic
- Wrote 26 "Dialogues" about the afterlife
	- Socrates was the central character
		- Was a real person, mentor of Plato
		- Original dialogues were likely records, but in later ones Socrates was a mouthpiece for Plato's idea
- Difficult to separate Plato's own ideas from those of his teacher Socrates

#### The Theory of Forms
- AKA The theory of ideas
- "What makes something real?"
	- Solid
	- Will it look like this tomorrow?
		- What about 10 years from now?
			- Reveals that it's not a pemanent thing
- Plato believes that "realness" is defined by unchangingness
	- Pretty much all matter in the universe is unreal by this definition
		- Including people
	- If the physical world is all unreal, then what is?
	- Even ideas and ideas of objects aren't truly real
- Claims that the only things that don't change are the FORMS of these objects and ideas
	- Believed that these forms exist beyond reality and humanity
		- That we saw the forms before we were born
- Believes that learning is actually the act of remembering things that we used to know before we were born

##### The cave analogy
- Born in a cave, but is only capable of looking directly at a wall
	- Can't turn head or anything
	- Comparable to the current state of artificial intelligence?
- Shadows are put on the wall from the light of a fire, with a platform between
	- The shadows represent the physical world and objects
	- Pale imitations of the true forms of things
- To them, the shapes that appear on the wall ARE their reality
- Believes that sometimes these people are able to break their chains, and discover the true reality of the cave
	- It's painful, not used to using those muscles
	- They are unable to convince those who are still chained
	- They will eventually leave the cave
		- They are blinded by the bright sunlight, but eventually acclimate
- Believes that the "Real World" can only be perceived when we leave the cave
- The body is temporary, but the soul is immortal

> Can something have multiple forms?
> IE a stool, which is arguably a table or a chair


##### Particular Dialogues
- Phaedo
	- Socrates argues very effectively for the theory of forms
	- Accused of corrupting the youth, and denying the gods
	- The Phaedo takes place when he is about to be executed
		- Had a chance to escape, but declined because it would disrespect everything he's fought for
		- Talks with his young friends about the immortality of the soul
			- Two possibilities:
				- Nothing
					- The soul is snuffed out
					- Like a sound, deep sleep
						- Claims it's very comfortable
				- The soul is immortal
					- Wishes it was this one
					- Wants to go to where all the other souls are so that he can talk to them and harass them just like he did in his mortal life
					- Rejects common ("vulgar") ideas of the afterlife and [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Hades (Place)]]
					- Believes the soul experiences many different incarnations, and that good souls eventually go to "[[Unsorted/Rewarding afterlife\|The Place of True Hades]]"
						- Which is invisible and pure and noble
						- Towards the "Good and wise [[Unsorted/God (Monotheistic)\|God (Monotheistic)]]"
					- [[Unsorted/Afterlives#Sorting\|Afterlives#Sorting]]
						- Neutral souls
							- Purified of their wrongdoings in a lake
							- Drink from the river Lethe, which causes them to forget everything
							- [[Unsorted/Reincarnation\|Reborn]] as a human or animal
						- Bad souls are tied to the physical world
							- [[Unsorted/Reincarnation\|Reincarnated]], potentially as an animal who will be karmically suitable to to their previous life's [[Unsorted/Sins\|errors]]
						- Worst souls are hurled into [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Tartarus]] and never come out
							- IE for murder
							- Souls who have done terrible but not unforgivable things
								- IE
									- Violence to a mother or father then repented
									- Took the life of another under extenuating circumstances
								- Also go to [[Class - Roots of Hell/Punishing afterlife\|Tartarus]], but only for a year
									- They appeal for mercy from those who they wronged
									- If denied, they stay for another year
- Gorgias
	- Speaks of the god Rhadamanthus
		- Sorts the dead
			- Stamps deeds as curable or incurable:
				- 'license and luxury and insolence and incontinence' 
				- Jokes that the incurable ones tend to be politicians
- Phaedrus
	- Describes the [[Unsorted/Soul\|Soul]] as having wings
		- Perfect souls fly upwards
		- Imperfect souls drop to the Earth
- The Republic
	- Discusses what a utopian society would look like
		- Something like "If we are to have a just society, this is how crazy it would have to be"
		- Absolute gender equality
		- Children raised in common #based
			- No parent should know exactly who their kid is
			- Every adult should look at every child in the city as if they are their child
			- Every child should look at every adult as if they are their parent
		- Philosopher kings
	- Is where the cave analogy comes from
	- Ends with the story of Er
		- One of the first accounts of a near-death experience
		- Er was badly wounded in an ancient battle, thought to be dead
			- For 12 days
		- Woke up on a funeral pyre
		- He described a vision he had of the afterlife while he was dead
			- Virtuous souls ascend to the heavens on the right
			- Evil souls descend on the left
				- Met by wild men of fiery aspect and attacked
				- On the 12th day the souls are reincarnated
					- Drink from the river Lethe
		- Instead of being reincarnated he just woke up on the funeral pyre




### Socrates
- Didn't write anything himself, was recorded and re-invented by Plato
	- Later is used as a mouthpiece for Plato's own ideas
- Reputation for running around town and speaking his mind
	- Tried to reveal the ignorance of influential figures and experts
- Clever speaker
	- Often started with compliments
	- Asked a series of yes/no questions
		- Waits for contradictions and points them out
			- To comedic effect?

### Pythagoreas
- Believed that numbers were the fundamental reality of the universe
- Also believed in reincarnation
	- "Transmigration of the soul"
	- Claimed to remember some of his past lives

### Epicurus (341-270 BCE)
- Believed that atoms was the fundamental reality of the universe
- Strongly influenced later atheist thinkers
	- If there are gods, they are far away and don't care about humans
		- And claims that that is a good thing
			- Believed that one of the main sources of human unhappiness is fear of death
				- And fear of punishment in the afterlife
			- Argued that when we die we just break into our component atoms and re-merge back with the universe
	- "If God listened to the prayers of men, all men would quickly have perished: for they are forever praying for evil against one another"


## [[Unsorted/Aristotle\|Aristotle]]
- Has extreme influence on later western thought
	- Including Dante, who loved [[Unsorted/Aristotle\|Aristotle]]
		- [[Unsorted/Dante's Inferno\|Dante's Inferno]]
- Ideas of the *human* [[Unsorted/Soul\|Soul]]
	- Central to our capacity for reason
		- Which animals don't have
	- Doesn't believe in the immortality of the soul
- None of his writings have survived
	- All of the original works (hundreds) were lost
	- The text that has survived are likely notes from students
		- Pain in the ass to read
	- His original texts are described as having a "honeyed sweetness"
